{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2659c60d-54be-43fb-b33a-01a4d87a88a8","content":"## Connecting MCP Inspector to a C# stdio server\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n  *(or point to a built DLL: `dotnet /path/to/YourServer.dll`)*\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Debug your tools:**\n- Use the **Tools** tab to list and invoke tools with test inputs.\n- Use the **Resources** tab to browse exposed resources.\n- Watch the **request/response log** pane for raw JSON-RPC messages.\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout only**. Any logging or debug output must go to **stderr**, or it will corrupt the protocol stream.\n- If using `Console.WriteLine` for logging, switch to `Console.Error.WriteLine`.\n- You can pass environment variables in the Inspector UI if your server needs them (e.g., API keys).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b54f1ce-1eeb-4817-b03e-e658fc89e8bf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I don't need to search the codebase for this. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"842F:A6E4B:100F935:141C72E:69FFDAF3"},"id":"c8482459-f3d6-4c5a-9dd2-2b35419e1ae2","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:10:20.879Z","parentId":"669acd3f-9eeb-493b-9263-9a2cc465251d"}
